<?xml-model ../out/tls1.rnc application/relax-ng-compact-syntax?><div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:mods="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3" xmlns:tls="http://tls.kanripo.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" type="concept" xml:id="uuid-6f7adb7e-4a80-498a-9ad8-5886013168de"><head>RUB</head><list type="altnames"><item>MASSAGE</item><item>KNEAD</item><item>STROKE</item><item>PAT</item><item>SCOUR</item><item>RUB</item><item>CLEAN</item><item>CLEANSE</item></list><list type="translations"><item xml:lang="zh">摩擦</item><item xml:lang="och">磨</item></list><div type="definition"><p>TOUCH AND PRESS WHILE MOVING ALONG something.</p></div><div type="notes"><div type="old-chinese-criteria"><p>1. The current general word for rubbing the surface of something is mó 磨.</p><p>2. Qǐē 切 adds to the notion of rubbing that of cutting and carving in order to produce smooth surfaces.</p><p>3. Fú 拂 is a very mild form of rubbing and wiping.</p><p>4. Cuō 磋 is an archaic word referring to the rubbing and polishing of surfaces.</p><p>5. Zhuó 琢 refers specifically to the polishing of jade.</p><p>6. Wèn 抆 refers specifically to the wiping off of tears.</p><p>NB: this is notoriously difficult to separate off from POLISH: perhaps we should collapse these two.]</p></div><div type="modern-chinese-criteria"><p>揉</p><p>撫摸</p><p>磨擦</p><p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p></div></div><div type="pointers"><list type="taxonymy"><item><ref target="#uuid-e4f27013-ca16-4fdf-b7a1-075d72b062cb">POLISH</ref></item><item><ref target="#uuid-ba82af8b-b1d9-4907-baec-da112c8751a2">SCRATCH</ref></item><item><ref target="#uuid-cb0086fd-2b5e-46a7-a9fd-a071eef8a7a3">WIPE</ref></item></list></div><div type="source-references"><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-60d39cc0-d76b-4275-8490-886ace4204be">BUCK 1988</ref><title>A Dictionary of Selected Synonyms in the Principal Indo-European Languages</title><biblScope unit="page">9.31